Allan,

To the best of my knowledge, JUnit 4 will automatically ensure that 
setup and teardown methods from superclasses are called at the 
appropriate time.

    David Saff

Allan Halme wrote:

&gt; Do we know whether JUnit 4 will be resolving this &quot;design smell&quot;, i.e. 
&gt; will
&gt; it no longer require subclasses of TestCase to explicitly remember to 
&gt; call
&gt; super.setUp and super.tearDown() ?
&gt;
&gt; One other thing that has to be remembered, that I always initially 
&gt; forget,
&gt; is that--at least in my test fixtures--you&#39;ll want to call super.setUp()
&gt; _first_ in your subclass&#39;s overriding method, but you&#39;ll want to call
&gt; super.tearDown() correspondingly _last_ in its overriding method ...
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; On 27/07/05, Cedric Beust &lt;cbeust@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;  &gt; From: junit@yahoogroups.com [mailto:junit@yahoogroups.com] On
&gt; &gt; &gt; Behalf Of Russell Gold
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; On 7/26/05, Dave Brosius &lt;dbrosius@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; I have it in my head that the junit folks recommend always calling
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; super.setUp/tearDown from a user declared setUp/tearDown,
&gt; &gt; &gt; even if the
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; JUnit test in question is directly derived from TestCase. However i
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; cannot find any written (web page) recommendation to so. Is
&gt; &gt; &gt; this still
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; the case? Is there a documented recommendation some where?
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Even if you cannot find the page, this is definitely a good
&gt; &gt; &gt; idea. If you decide at a later time to have your test case
&gt; &gt; &gt; extend something besides TestCase, your invocations of
&gt; &gt; &gt; super.setUp/tearDown will already be in place.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Yup, it&#39;s the best way, but it&#39;s unfortunate that JUnit forces you to do
&gt; &gt; that, because having to call super is a clear design smell in OO design
&gt; &gt; (because if somebody subclasses your class and forget to call super, it
&gt; &gt; will
&gt; &gt; break). In short, it defeats the purpose of polymorphism.
&gt; &gt;
